Japan, China, South Korea, Singapore: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   A n i l   V a r m a
-- 
2011-05-25T22:43:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-25/japan-china-south-korea-asian-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The finance ministry will release data at 8:50 a.m. on
Japanese and foreign investment flows into domestic and overseas
securities during the week ended May 20. The ministry will sell
1.1 trillion yen ($13.4 billion) of 20-year  government bonds  and
announce a coupon for the new securities at 10:30 a.m.  The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond maturing in
March 2021 was at 1.12 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading
Co. The yen traded at 82.02 as of 7:37 a.m. in Tokyo.  China :  China Development Bank  plans to sell a combined 30
billion yuan ($4.6 billion) of three- and seven-year bonds,
while the central bank will sell 1 billion yuan of three-month
notes.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.84
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.4934.  India : The commerce ministry will report food inflation for
the week ended May 14. Prices rose 7.47 percent in the previous
week from a year earlier.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.37
percent. The rupee was at 45.34.  Singapore: Industrial production fell 8.6 percent in April
from a year earlier after climbing 22 percent the previous month,
according to the median estimate of economists surveyed by
Bloomberg before data due today.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.24 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.2492.  South Korea : A consumer confidence index for May will be
released today. The sentiment index rose to 100 in April from 98
in March.  The yield on South Korea’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.57 percent. The won was at 1,101.45 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anil Varma in Mumbai at 
 avarma3@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at   shendry@bloomberg.net  